Great, this is a classic LLD + design pattern combo (Mediator + Auction System) — very commonly asked. I’ll simplify and structure it so you can explain confidently in interviews + actually design it.

🧠 1️⃣ Mediator Pattern — One Line
Objects communicate through a central mediator instead of directly with each other.
🎯 Core Problem It Solves
❌ Without Mediator
Bidder A ↔ Bidder B ↔ Bidder C ↔ Bidder D

👉 Everyone talks to everyone
👉 Too many dependencies
👉 Tight coupling ❌

✅ With Mediator
Bidder → Auction → Bidder

👉 Central controller
👉 Loose coupling ✅

🧩 Real-World Examples
🏷️ Online Auction System
✈️ Air Traffic Control
💬 Chat Application
🎮 Multiplayer Game Lobby
Visual Idea
4
🧠 Key Insight
Objects don’t know each other  
They only know the mediator
🧩 Components (VERY IMPORTANT)
🟦 1. Mediator Interface
interface AuctionMediator {
    void addBidder(Colleague bidder);
    void placeBid(Colleague bidder, int amount);
}
🟩 2. Concrete Mediator
class Auction implements AuctionMediator {
    List<Colleague> bidders = new ArrayList<>();

    public void addBidder(Colleague bidder) {
        bidders.add(bidder);
    }

    public void placeBid(Colleague bidder, int amount) {
        for (Colleague b : bidders) {
            if (b != bidder) {
                b.receiveBidNotification(bidder.getName(), amount);
            }
        }
    }
}
🟨 3. Colleague Interface
interface Colleague {
    void placeBid(int amount);
    void receiveBidNotification(String bidder, int amount);
    String getName();
}
🟧 4. Concrete Colleague (Bidder)
class Bidder implements Colleague {
    String name;
    AuctionMediator mediator;

    public Bidder(String name, AuctionMediator mediator) {
        this.name = name;
        this.mediator = mediator;
        mediator.addBidder(this);
    }

    public void placeBid(int amount) {
        mediator.placeBid(this, amount);
    }

    public void receiveBidNotification(String bidder, int amount) {
        System.out.println(name + " notified: " + bidder + " bid " + amount);
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}
🟥 5. Client
AuctionMediator auction = new Auction();

Bidder A = new Bidder("A", auction);
Bidder B = new Bidder("B", auction);

A.placeBid(1000);
B.placeBid(2000);
🔁 Flow Explained
Step 1
A places bid → mediator
Step 2
Mediator notifies all others
Step 3
B receives → reacts
🔥 Why This Is Powerful
✅ 1. Loose Coupling
Bidders don’t know each other
✅ 2. Centralized Logic
All rules in one place (mediator)
✅ 3. Easy to Extend
Add new bidder → no changes in others
❌ Tradeoff
Mediator can become complex (God object)
🆚 Mediator vs Observer (IMPORTANT)
Mediator
Communication control

Objects talk via mediator

Bidder → mediator → bidder

Observer
Event notification

Subject → notify all observers

No interaction logic

🔥 Difference
Mediator = coordination  
Observer = broadcast
🆚 Mediator vs Proxy
Mediator
Manages communication between multiple objects
Proxy
Controls access to ONE object
🧠 When to Use Mediator

Use when:

✔ Many objects interacting
✔ Complex dependencies
✔ Want loose coupling
✔ Central coordination needed
🚀 Interview Tips (VERY IMPORTANT)
❓ If interviewer says:
Design chat app / auction / air traffic

👉 Think:

MEDIATOR
❓ If many objects talking to each other?

👉 Use mediator

❓ If communication is centralized?

👉 Use mediator

🧠 Memory Trick
“Don’t talk to each other, talk to the boss”

👉 Boss = Mediator

🔥 Final Mental Model
Colleagues = Users  
Mediator = Server
🎯 Perfect Interview Answer
Mediator pattern is a behavioral design pattern that reduces coupling between objects by making them communicate through a central mediator instead of directly interacting with each other.